  abstract={This chapter explores the use of vulnerability chains within a cybersecurity program, specifically in the remediation aspect of Vulnerability Management Programs. Vulnerability chaining attacks have only recently become part of the mainstream conversation of vulnerability management, but they have been leveraged by advanced persistent threat groups for many years. Based on that data, it's absolutely possible for attackers to leverage older vulnerabilities to conduct critical vulnerability chaining attacks. The chapter provides specific vendor examples. It includes different examples of how users can be a component of vulnerability chaining, including phishing, business email compromise, and other social engineering tactics. Vulnerability chaining attacks can be used to compromise all systems, drop ransomware, or steal corporate data to sell on the dark web. Many security practitioners may already be aware of the vulnerability chaining attacks leveraged against users and systems.},
