  abstract={This chapter sets out many cyber security terms which are frequently encountered or used with a specific context within the domain of cyber threat intelligence. Cyber threat intelligence is the study of threats. Importantly, threats do not necessarily need to be actively malicious. Threats can be accidental or forces of nature. Cyber security is about managing risks. The business email compromise is a type of scam that relies on human error. Threat actors can range from individuals working on their own who attack systems for no other motivation than to have fun or to demonstrate their technical prowess, to teams of salaried government employees who launch attacks to further the geopolitical aims of a nation state. Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures are descriptions of how a threat actor goes about attempting to achieve their desired goal.},
